---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ChapterSummary from '../../components/ChapterSummary.astro';

const chapters = [
  { href: '#identity', label: 'Identity before translation' },
  { href: '#environment', label: 'Powerful environment' },
  { href: '#pace', label: 'YGO pace, Magic structure' },
  { href: '#archetypes', label: 'Archetype promises' },
  { href: '#source', label: 'Source-backed design' },
  { href: '#avoids', label: 'What the cube avoids' },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Cube philosophy — YGO × MTG"
  description="Design philosophy behind translating Yu-Gi-Oh! identities into a high-power Magic cube."
  theme="home"
>
  <article class="page-shell info-page philosophy-page">
    <header>
      <p>YGO × MTG</p>
      <h1>Cube philosophy</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Preserve how a Yu-Gi-Oh! card feels, not every literal line. Rebuild its
        role inside Magic’s rules until it is recognizable, interactive, and
        worth drafting.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="info-layout">
      <div class="info-content">
        <section id="identity">
          <h2>Identity before translation</h2>
          <p>
            This cube is adaptation, not transcription. Names, themes, signature
            play patterns, and tactical purpose survive. Costs, statistics,
            timing, and wording change when Magic’s engine needs them to. A
            successful card creates the same decision or emotional beat without
            pretending both games share a rules system.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="environment">
          <h2>A closed, intentionally powerful environment</h2>
          <p>
            Cards are balanced against this cube, not normal Limited. Games
            support several actions per turn, fast development, frequent Extra
            Deck summons, strong tutors, and graveyard recursion. Interaction
            must be equally strong so speed creates decisions rather than
            deterministic openings, infinite loops, or non-games.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="pace">
          <h2>Yu-Gi-Oh! pace, Magic structure</h2>
          <div class="principle-grid">
            <article>
              <h3>Readable compression</h3>
              <p>
                Repeated long effects become stable cube keywords. Card text
                stays concise enough to play at the table while this site
                provides full definitions.
              </p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>Real costs</h3>
              <p>
                Mana, cards, materials, tempo, Grave, and exile are deliberate
                resources. Explosive effects demand sequencing and expose
                windows for interaction.
              </p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>Recognizable decks</h3>
              <p>
                Archetypes remain coherent packages, not piles of references.
                Each should advertise a plan, reward mastery, and overlap with
                the rest of the cube without losing identity.
              </p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <h3>Rules honesty</h3>
              <p>
                Summons, targets, costs, triggers, and zones use explicit Magic
                semantics. Flavor never excuses ambiguous or hidden rules.
              </p>
            </article>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section id="archetypes">
          <h2>Archetype promises</h2>
          <dl class="rule-glossary">
            <div>
              <dt>Burning Abyss</dt><dd>
                Small black Fiends turn sacrifice and Grave movement into
                durable value, then climb into Xyz and Synchro threats.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt>Shaddoll</dt><dd>
                Control and Fusion gameplay rewards face-down planning plus
                carefully sending cards to Grave.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt>Nekroz</dt><dd>
                A blue Ritual toolbox wins through search, hand utility,
                resource sequencing, and measured anti-Extra Deck control—not
                immediate lethal combos.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt>Spellbook</dt><dd>
                Wizard and spell chains turn accumulated knowledge into
                incremental advantage while printed alternative costs create
                deliberate burst turns.
              </dd>
            </div>
          </dl>
        </section>

        <section id="source">
          <h2>Source-backed by design</h2>
          <p>
            Canonical MSE projects own card-by-card text, cost, statistics,
            type, frame, and render. Rules documents own reusable mechanics.
            Original Yu-Gi-Oh! records preserve traceability. This separation
            lets cards evolve without quietly splitting the source of truth.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="avoids">
          <h2>What the cube avoids</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>Literal conversions that break Magic timing or vocabulary.</li>
            <li>
              Free power without deck-building, material, or tempo tension.
            </li>
            <li>Infinite loops and non-interactive endings.</li>
            <li>Generic good-stuff cards that erase archetype identity.</li>
            <li>Rules text duplicated across docs and card sources.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Goal: every card should make a Yu-Gi-Oh! player recognize its soul
            and a Magic player trust how it works.
          </p>
        </section>
      </div>

      <ChapterSummary items={chapters} />
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
